ds=read_csv("C:\\Users\\yllw1\\OneDrive\\Desktop\\M&M Learning\\Classification Project\\DEV _ March Madness.csv")
## Rows: 8315 Columns: 151
##  Column specification 
## Delimiter: ","
## chr  (14): Short Conference Name, Mapped Conference Name, Mapped ESPN Team N...
## dbl (137): Season, Adjusted Temo, Adjusted Tempo Rank, Raw Tempo, Raw Tempo ...
## 
##  Use `spec()` to retrieve the full column specification for this data.
##  Specify the column types or set `show_col_types = FALSE` to quiet this message.
library(rpart)
library(rpart.plot)
library(caret)
library(ipred)
library(ggplot2)


# Ensure we have the Seed_Class variable
if(!"Seed_Class" %in% colnames(ds)) {
  ds$Seed_Class <- NA  # Initialize with NA
  ds$Seed_Class[ds$Seed %in% c("1", "2", "3", "4", "5", "6", "7", "8")] <- "Low"
  ds$Seed_Class[ds$Seed %in% c("9", "10", "11", "12", "13", "14", "15", "16")] <- "High"
  ds$Seed_Class[ds$Seed == "Not In a Post-Season Tournament"] <- "Not In Tournament"

  # Convert to factor with appropriate levels
  ds$Seed_Class <- factor(ds$Seed_Class, levels = c("Low", "High", "Not In Tournament"))
}

# Filter out teams not in tournament for our analysis
ds_tournament <- ds[ds$Seed_Class != "Not In Tournament", ]
ds_tournament$Seed_Class <- droplevels(ds_tournament$Seed_Class)

# Select expanded set of variables for our analysis
# Using the variables suggested: offensive and defensive efficiency, eFG%, TO%, OR%, and FT rate
tree_data <- ds_tournament[, c(
  "Adjusted Offensive Efficiency",
  "Adjusted Defensive Efficiency",
  "eFGPct",                        # Effective Field Goal Percentage
  "TOPct",                         # Turnover Percentage
  "ORPct",                         # Offensive Rebounding Percentage
  "FTRate",                        # Free Throw Rate
  "Seed_Class"
)]

# Remove any rows with NA values
tree_data <- na.omit(tree_data)

# For simplicity in modeling, rename columns without spaces
colnames(tree_data) <- c("AdjOffEff", "AdjDefEff", "eFGPct", "TOPct", "ORPct", "FTRate", "SeedClass")
# Split into training and testing sets (70/30 split)
set.seed(239)  # For reproducibility

# Separate data by Seed_Class
low_seeds <- tree_data[tree_data$SeedClass == "Low", ]
high_seeds <- tree_data[tree_data$SeedClass == "High", ]

# Calculate 70% training size for each group
low_train_size <- floor(0.7 * nrow(low_seeds))
high_train_size <- floor(0.7 * nrow(high_seeds))

# Sample for training set
low_train_indices <- sample(1:nrow(low_seeds), low_train_size)
high_train_indices <- sample(1:nrow(high_seeds), high_train_size)

# Create training and testing datasets
train_data <- rbind(
  low_seeds[low_train_indices, ],
  high_seeds[high_train_indices, ]
)

test_data <- rbind(
  low_seeds[-low_train_indices, ],
  high_seeds[-high_train_indices, ]
)
#### Step 1: Classification Tree with Expanded Variables
set.seed(252)
class_tree <- rpart(SeedClass ~ .,
                    data = train_data,
                    method = "class")

# Plot the tree
rpart.plot(class_tree, main = "Classification Tree for NCAA Tournament Seeds")

# Plot CP
plotcp(class_tree)

printcp(class_tree)
## 
## Classification tree:
## rpart(formula = SeedClass ~ ., data = train_data, method = "class")
## 
## Variables actually used in tree construction:
## [1] AdjDefEff AdjOffEff eFGPct    FTRate   
## 
## Root node error: 659/1785 = 0.36919
## 
## n= 1785 
## 
##         CP nsplit rel error  xerror     xstd
## 1 0.051593      0   1.00000 1.00000 0.030939
## 2 0.018209      2   0.89681 0.91351 0.030310
## 3 0.010000      5   0.84219 0.88467 0.030066
# Find CP that minimizes the error
min_cp <- class_tree$cptable[which.min(class_tree$cptable[,"xerror"]),"CP"]
cat("Optimal complexity parameter (CP):", min_cp, "\n")
## Optimal complexity parameter (CP): 0.01
#### Step 2: Prune the Tree
pruned_tree <- prune(class_tree, cp = min_cp)
rpart.plot(pruned_tree, main = "Pruned Classification Tree for NCAA Tournament Seeds")

#### Step 3: Predict with Both Trees
# Predictions with default tree
pred_tree1 <- predict(class_tree, test_data, type = "class")

# Confusion matrix for default tree
cm_tree1 <- table(test_data$SeedClass, pred_tree1)
print("Confusion Matrix for Default Tree:")
## [1] "Confusion Matrix for Default Tree:"
print(cm_tree1)
##       pred_tree1
##        Low High
##   Low  396   87
##   High 158  125
# Accuracy for default tree
acc_tree1 <- mean(test_data$SeedClass == pred_tree1)
cat("Accuracy for Default Tree:", acc_tree1, "\n")
## Accuracy for Default Tree: 0.6801567
#0.6801 accuracy

# Predictions with pruned tree
pred_tree2 <- predict(pruned_tree, test_data, type = "class")

# Confusion matrix for pruned tree
cm_tree2 <- table(test_data$SeedClass, pred_tree2)
print("Confusion Matrix for Pruned Tree:")
## [1] "Confusion Matrix for Pruned Tree:"
print(cm_tree2)
##       pred_tree2
##        Low High
##   Low  396   87
##   High 158  125
# Accuracy for pruned tree
acc_tree2 <- mean(test_data$SeedClass == pred_tree2)
cat("Accuracy for Pruned Tree:", acc_tree2, "\n")
## Accuracy for Pruned Tree: 0.6801567
#0.68

set.seed(252)

                         data = train_data,
                         nbagg = 150,

# Predict with bagging model

#### Step 5: Bagging with Caret
set.seed(252)
caret_bag <- train(SeedClass ~ .,
                   data = train_data,
                   method = "treebag",
                   trControl = trainControl("cv", number = 10),
                   importance = TRUE)

# Variable importance
